{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game revolves around private values for red and blue chips, with green as a known common-value chip ($0.50 to everyone). Bear values blue chips the most ($1.00) and red chips moderately ($0.60). Buffalo values blue highly ($0.70) and red weakly ($0.10). Goose values both red and blue very little ($0.10 each). All players know their own values, see everyone’s chip counts and trade history, but do not know others’ exact values; they infer motives from which bundles are offered or accepted. The key surplus comes from moving blue chips away from Goose (who barely values them) to Bear and Buffalo (who value them). Red chips are also more valuable in Bear’s hands than in Buffalo’s or Goose’s, but the blue surplus is bigger and clearer. Because greens are common value, they are safe, transparent currency-like objects players can use to pay for more or less valuable reds/blues without raising suspicion about their private values.\n\nStrategically, Bear is the natural aggregator of blue chips and will want to buy blue from Goose (and possibly from Buffalo) using green and red. Buffalo will seek to buy blue cheaply and sell red, and may also try to sell blue if they infer Bear values blue more. Goose, with low values for both red and blue, is happy to give up these chips for green or other chips if the calculator shows even small positive gains. But Goose does not know that their red/blue are undervalued relative to others and so might accept trades that yield modest calculator gains even when these are very favorable to Bear or Buffalo.\n\nBargaining dynamics reflect uncertainty and signaling. If someone persistently tries to buy a specific color, others infer that color might be valuable to them and become tougher sellers, demanding more green or asking for the other non-green color in return. Because non-senders respond simultaneously and only one accepting recipient is chosen at random, senders face an additional risk: if they offer a clearly profitable trade for both other players, both may accept, and the sender loses control over which partner they trade with. This tends to push proposals toward being particularly attractive to a target type (e.g., the obviously weak holder like Goose) or just barely acceptable to one counterpart but not the other.\n\nOver three rounds with each player proposing once per round, early turns will likely be exploratory, revealing how eager others are to trade certain colors. Later turns will exploit discovered arbitrage, especially moving blue from Goose to Bear and/or Buffalo. Because chip counts carry over across turns, a profitable early trade can reshape later bargaining power and options. The forecast path below follows a plausible sequence where Bear successfully consolidates blue from Goose using green and red, Buffalo manages to acquire some extra blue early, and Goose steadily exchanges low-valued blue/red for green or small positive expected gains, without fully recognizing others’ higher valuations.",
