  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features private values for red and blue chips and a common value for green chips. All players start with 10 of each color. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone and is therefore a neutral store of value; red and blue are where the gains from trade lie. Badger values both red and blue at $0.80, Camel values red at $0.60 and blue at $0.40, and Squid values red at $0.20 and blue at $0.60. This implies large potential surplus between Badger and Squid on red chips (Badger likes red a lot, Squid dislikes it) and moderate potential surplus between Badger and Camel on blue chips (Badger likes blue more). Camel is moderately between Badger and Squid on red, and lowest on blue. However, the players do not know each other’s values; they only see their own surplus figures per proposal and know the public range for values. Strategic uncertainty arises because any proposal must be acceptable to at least one opponent based on that opponent’s unseen valuations, and acceptances are simultaneous with random tie-breaking. Proposers will tend to start conservatively—offering trades that are at least weakly beneficial for themselves at any acceptance and that they hope give enough surplus to at least one counterpart. Over time, observing which offers are accepted or declined reveals partial information about others’ tastes (e.g., frequent acceptance of red-for-blue suggests higher value for the bought color). Because there are only three rounds and each player has one proposal per round, they face a trade-off between being generous enough to induce acceptance and being greedy to maximize surplus per successful trade. As an outside observer with full information, we can anticipate that mutually beneficial red-for-blue trades between Badger and Squid generate the largest surplus, while Camel more cautiously adjusts holdings using green as a flexible medium when direct red–blue swaps seem too risky. The forecasted game below follows this logic: Badger gradually tests the market to move toward more red and blue that it values highly, Squid seeks to offload low-value red and pick up blue, and Camel experiments with small, safe adjustments around red and green when possible. Not all value-increasing trades will actually occur, because the players do not see each other’s payoff tables and must infer them indirectly via acceptances and rejections.",
