d player (peacock for red, swan for blue).\n\nOver only three rounds (nine total turns), players have limited time to learn about others’ types. Early offers will be relatively mild and information-seeking, giving at least one respondent a small gain while preserving margin for the proposer. As more trades occur, revealed acceptance patterns will suggest who especially values which colors, but with so few turns, players may never fully exploit the theoretically available gains. The random recipient rule means proposers tailor trades that are acceptable to both potential partners but slightly more attractive to the partner they hope is selected, accepting some probability-weighted loss of control. Overall, the likely game path includes modest, low-risk trades that move chips toward players with moderately higher valuations rather than aggressive or highly skewed bargains.\n\nIn the forecast below, the game path is one plausible, incentive-compatible trajectory where everyone remains locally rational given their private information and observed history, and no player knowingly takes a negative-surplus trade.",
