  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game creates strong, but hidden, incentives for players to swap RED and BLUE chips in opposite directions, with GREEN serving as a neutral currency. Each player starts symmetric in quantity (10 of each color) but asymmetric in value: Zebra loves RED (0.80) and dislikes BLUE (0.30); Turtle loves BLUE (0.70) and dislikes RED (0.10); Gorilla lies in between (BLUE 0.40, RED 0.20). GREEN is common value (0.50) for all players, so it can be treated as cash that nobody wants to lose value in, but everyone is willing to reshuffle if it helps them convert low-value colors into high-value ones.\n\nBecause values are private, each player knows only their own payoffs and only a loose public range for others. They can, however, always see their own net gain/loss for any proposed trade using the calculator. This makes acceptance behavior close to myopic: if a trade gives a strictly positive net gain in dollar value (ignoring risk of future offers), a player is very likely to accept; if it is negative, they almost surely reject. Indifference regions or very small gains may be sensitive to expectations about future trades, but in a short three-round game with three proposals per round, most participants are inclined to take visibly positive deals.\n\nThe underlying surplus opportunities are large. For example, swapping BLUE from Zebra (who values it at 0.30) to Turtle (0.70) can generate up to 0.40 of surplus per BLUE, and swapping RED from Turtle (0.10) to Zebra (0.80) can generate up to 0.70 per RED. Gorilla can act as either a middleman or a direct trading partner: Gorilla values BLUE more than Zebra but less than Turtle, and values RED more than Turtle but much less than Zebra. That makes simple, straightforward bilateral trades extremely attractive: Zebra offers BLUE to Turtle for RED; Turtle offers RED to Zebra for BLUE; Gorilla trades BLUE to Zebra for GREEN (or RED) and trades RED to Turtle for GREEN (or BLUE). All of these have ranges where both sides gain.\n\nThe main frictions are uncertainty about others’ values and the randomization when multiple responders accept. Proposers cannot target a specific partner if both non-senders like a deal; their counterpart is selected at random. That encourages proposers to design trades such that (a) at least one partner strictly gains and (b) the expected outcome for the proposer is positive even if either partner accepts. Because all three have high private value on GREEN (0.50) relative to at least one color, nobody wants to give away GREEN too cheaply—but GREEN is also appealing as a safe chip to offer when a player is trying to buy either RED or BLUE without signaling too much about their own valuations.\n\nOver the three rounds (nine total proposals), a likely dynamic is early, exploratory offers with modest but clear gains for the proposer that test the response behavior of others, followed by more directed cross-trades that exploit what has been implicitly learned: Zebra will try to accumulate RED while offloading BLUE; Turtle will try to accumulate BLUE while offloading RED; Gorilla will opportunistically convert low-value RED into BLUE or GREEN and possibly sell some BLUE to Zebra or buy RED from Turtle if it can be flipped later. Because the horizon is short and players cannot explicitly coordinate, not all potential surplus will be realized, but we should expect a sequence of simple two-chip trades that each side’s calculator labels as profitable, and very few accepted trades that create a loss for any participant.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs a plausible full game path where players act in line with these incentives, designing proposals that look modestly profitable from their own private perspective and are often, but not always, attractive enough to be accepted by at least one partner. Rejections occur when the surplus split appears too skewed or when responders hope for better future opportunities.",
