ance to trade suggests it is high-value. The random recipient rule when multiple accept introduces further uncertainty: a proposer cannot target a specific partner, so they must design offers that are safe and profitable regardless of which accepting player is matched. By the final round, players often make more aggressive, one-sided proposals to lock in last gains, especially those who see clear arbitrage opportunities between a low-value holder and a high-value seeker of a chip color.\n\nIn this forecast, trades are chosen to be consistent with each player seeking positive surplus on every accepted trade, limited learning over a single short game, and boundedly rational attempts to piece together others’ preferences from limited evidence.",
